The better world is already here
KOPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have been discussing the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to plundering and war, and in which the growing production capacity of the past few decades has led to more pollution and global warming.
One of the sacred texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits of Growth, continues to influence the environmental movement today.
On the other hand, optimists claim that everything will get better – human health, living standard, environmental quality, and so on.
They are seen by their opponents as "economists of abundance" who trust the market, which allegedly solves all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a big story of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see whether the world is really getting better or worse.
This is what I have tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing a rating list for the past 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender ratios, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists have answered the same question: How high were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including forecasts up to 2050.
Using classic economic evaluations of all factors from mortality rates, health damage, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands up to higher hurricane risks due to global warming, the economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To estimate the extent of the problem, it is compared to the total available resources for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's consider the inequality of the sexes.
Basically, we had almost half of the world population excluded from production back then.
1900 there were only 15% of the workforce worldwide of female gender.
What are the losses that have arisen from this low share?
Even if we take into account the higher costs of educating women, and that someone has to do unpaid household work, the losses had a height of at least 17% of the world's GDP of 1900.
Today, with a higher female participation in employment and smaller income differences, the loss is 7% – and will probably fall to 4% by 2050.
It will probably be quite surprising that climate change will bring a growing net benefit from 1900 to 2025, which will rise to 1.5% of GDP per year.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs moderately, the benefit prevails.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 entries were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of the GDP.
Similarly, moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand more strongly than it creates new cooling needs, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of the GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, which cost about 0.2% of the GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, resulting in a loss of about 0.1%.
However, with further rising temperatures, costs increase and benefits decline, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs for the world, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and over the next few decades.
However, the rating list also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is air pollution indoors, which puts things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from air pollution in indoor spaces due to harmful emissions from cooking and heating. This corresponds to a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected to fall to 1% by 2050.
Mostly, health indicators have improved worldwide.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy hardly changed.
The size of the win since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and probably 76 years by 2050).
The biggest factor was the decline in infant mortality.
Even in 1970, for example, only 5% of newborns were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which has led to the rescue of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved through world peace in the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised another 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the 20th century were an astonishing 32% of the world's GDP.
Today, they have fallen back to about 11% and will halve again by 2050.
Even if the optimists are not right in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and much more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined issues show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even clearer.
Relatively to the resources available for their solution, the global problems have dramatically decreased.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no more problems.
Even if they have decreased in the areas of health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should gradually get used to the idea that the world has improved significantly.
Moreover, the rating list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not align our view of the future with the most terrifying stories or the loudest interest groups, but with objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
